At the Land Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public competition
In the Land Fund building in Plzen, anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives handed over the handcuffs to the local entrepreneur and real estate trader Lubos.
The latter had tried to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a request for restitution in such a way that the land proposed was obtained by a specific candidate.
The latter was to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"At the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider trading in the context of a public tender and competition," Plzen Prosecutor's Office chief Antonie Zelena told the Pravo newspaper, knowing that it is forbidden to provide more explanations because the investigation is ongoing.
The police released the 46-year-old entrepreneur after 24 hours.
To know how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate in view of the very little official information.
A question from Pravo, the spokesperson of the Land Fund Lubomira Cerna said that the police officers had actually made an arrest in Plzen at a separate workplace and this during the public competition.
"It was a customer and not an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has as its real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Land Law" and is set up when several beneficiaries of the right manifest themselves.
“These people are proposing, as part of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to restitution that must be settled before the value of the land is announced.”
"According to the proposed rights, a ranking of the buyers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights," the Fund spokesman explained.
Lubos G. had, of course, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the appeal and since he himself was also a beneficiary because he had bought a large number of rights to restitution, he had offered to the candidates on the ground not to participate in the competition.
And he was probably cashing in by withdrawing.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Land Fund).
It was included in the case of former FdT chief Vaclav Sankot, who was prosecuted for editing land for which the decision to set up a building had already been published.
For example, Lubos G. had obtained land for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place where the access road to the industrial area of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The town hall was forced to accept because otherwise it risked endangering the construction by blocking the land.
Households will pay an additional one hundred crowns monthly for housing.
From January, households will have to pay a supplement not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
From January onwards, families will have to draw up to a hundred crowns a month more than they do now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for the supply of water, and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be around 100 kroner per annum more for apartment households than at present.
However, all suppliers have decreased electricity prices given the sensitive development to encourage the manufacture of renewable energy, including photovoltaic cells.
The gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
We can therefore also count a hundred crowns more.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the larger municipalities that plan the price increase.
For example households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 kroner more per month, families in Liberec will pay more than 1000 kroner annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing an increase of 9 percent for water and sanitation in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change the pragmatists will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are increasing by 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will rise significantly, for example, in the 450 thousand apartments rented from January, that is to say at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2,500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase it up to 100 percent.
Those who do not agree with the new increase in rents will be brought to court by the company.
Regulated rents paid by people in nearly 300,000 apartments could rise by 10 percent next year.
Czech children get drunk with rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very gently.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in the hospital for recidivism are no exception.
This results from the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to the admissions of children's departments of hospitals.
"Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to be drunk."
"The trend is really towards strong alcohols," Ludek Pelikan, head of the children's department at Horovice Hospital in central Bohemia, told Pravo.
"When they manage to chip a bottle of papa in the closet, it is sometimes whiskey but it is the fernet and vodka that prevail.
“Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and so not smell it,” explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokesperson for the Motol hospital, also agrees.
"It's usually rum or fernet."
"It is now alcohol in fashion, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases it was slivovice that they brought back from the house," Jurinova added.
According to the Head of Department Pélikan, seeing drunk children between the ages of thirteen and fourteen at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced pediatrics for ten years, where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the surrounding area completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized like this four times
"She began her career at the age of twelve when she was brought with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood with in addition a mixture with ecstasy," described the doctor this particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Centre at a party."
"What's interesting is that it didn't seem strange to the mother that her daughter was absent for 48 hours," the head of the department said.
It is precisely the parents' unselfishness or their extraordinary tolerance of the fact that their offspring indulge in drinking that is the main cause of the development of children's alcoholism.
According to specialists, however, we do not talk about dependence, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the term alcoholic we mean a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena that result from it but that is not found in children."
"In those who use alcohol repeatedly, it is rather a significantly unfavorable socio-familial background," explained the Head of Department Pélikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunken children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are after emergency care taken home by parents or the police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children sitting down and drinking a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pélikan there are three seasonal waves that can be counted on: the day of the witches, St. Sylvester and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink out of spite after bad results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"Of course I experienced the witches' day an admission of 7 drunk children at once," said Pélikan.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital undergoing rehab under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the next day from the "hangover".
The morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off for this because they have a great night and then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them."
“They’re just amazed at where they are,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time this spoils the patients’ good mood at least with the bill to pay for their care.
Ambulance transport and intensive care bed hospitalization can go up to tens of thousands of kroner.
“From time to time, I applied this as a means of education by telling these children how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to repay a single evening,” Pelikan added.
However, according to him, the health insurance companies in their regression management, which should recover from the parents the burdens related to care, do not treat the cases of drunken children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two L-159 aircraft of the five in all, against which the Ministry of Defense exchanged transport aircraft Casa C-295M, took off on Tuesday for Seville in Spain where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of anyone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were until now in service in the Czech army and were in flight condition.
The three remaining aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of Vodochody's planes is currently unknown.
“The single-seat L-159 aircraft planned for the exchange were taken from long-storage aircraft without causing additional charges or investment for the Ministry of Defence.”
"The two-seater L-159 T1 was exchanged in the state," he told Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not be left without two-seaters since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek EADS has committed to introduce the aircraft in the equipment of some countries of the Alliance.
"The contract clearly states that the one that takes into account the L-159 aircraft is EADS and that they will be used for the training of pilots from NATO member countries."
"It is therefore the business of the one who is considering how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three more aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not issue a call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
the direction of the defense argued then that the exchange assures a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aéro Vodochody and used only 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft is likely to have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected in a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
An index finger longer than the ring finger is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have an index finger longer than the ring finger have a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that relative finger length serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men before age 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should get tested for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as a family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before age 60, the decrease in risk reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of the study but does not believe that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "fully demonstrated".
