The master glacier Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal characteristics of perfect ice.
Not only good taste, but also silky suppleness and good consistency are decisive.
However, Luciano does not forget during the training the icing on the cake of the national and, in general, southern superstructure: "Italian ice cream is simply the best: and then it still retains a hell of a dose of romanticism."
The first step in manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano pours the basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer that heats everything to 85 degrees thanks to an electronic program, then immediately cools to four degrees.
He then opens a tap installed on the machine: a pasteurized base white cream comes out, the foundation of all kinds of milk ice cream.
The trainer is immediately assailed by the question: Is it possible to make ice using only natural substances without stabilizer?
How can one give free rein to the personal pleasure of experimentation?
Mr. Luciano warns against being misled by the spirit of the time.
The one who only talks about ice cream "made from natural ingredients", may have nevertheless used stabilizers: most often a natural product, for example, guar seed flour obtained from guar bean.
It is obviously possible to make ice without using a stabilizer, only it must be sold within 24 hours, otherwise it collapses and the customer will not crunch anything other than ice pellets.
Some modifications of the basic mass are allowed.
This becomes more exciting with the aromas.
Master Luciano establishes the difference between the ingredients that one acquires in the fruit or confectionery department of the supermarket.
In addition, there is powder and pasta.
"suppliers will all try to pass you dozens of flavored ingredients."
"However, you should just try."
Either in the recipes of fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruit.
Or in ice creams made from the white base mass which, by adding eggs, becomes a yellow cream and is, when cocoa powder is added, the basis of all possible desserts to chocolate.
Now all participants in the course must move on to the use of ice machines.
Luciano invites them from time to time to make four kinds of ice cream: vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut with or without eggs in the base mass, with more or less vanilla flavor or other natural ingredients.
The different kinds of fruit ice cream are also subjected to the same experience.
More aromatic substances, more fruit purees: from the point of view of taste, this is not absolutely better.
The hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily have the taste of nuts, when it consists largely of hazelnuts.
The kiwi ice cream, very popular, is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizer.
“Only a well-balanced mixture can give the taste of an ice cream,” says Luciano.
Ice making is a calculation exercise: if you use peach puree with a lot of sugar, you need to reduce the amount of sugar in the basic recipe.
A sugar supplement is needed for lemon ice cream.
Luciano presents an apparatus with which he determines the sugar content of the different types of fruit (winegrowers use it to measure the degree of Oechsle in grape must).
Fortunately, the tables make the calculations easier.
The manufacture of ice no longer requires, as in the past, as much physical intervention.
It is not only the automatic manufacturing machine of the basic mass that helps.
There is also an apparatus in which the mixture of ice available is simultaneously beaten to make it unctuous and brought back to negative temperatures.
Despite all automations, slight breakdowns are not excluded.
Brazilian Gustavo dabbles in fruit puree from head to toe and thus splashes his fellow students when control of the colossal mixing bowl eludes him.
Master Luciano is of the opinion that "such an incident is likely to occur during each course: it is only a matter of time."
