We search in vain for the clouds of birds, as we usually find in wetlands: As soon as the outboard engine stops, a ghostly silence falls on this paradise of yesteryear that looks like a gas station by the smell it emits.
"What is happening here is a war on the environment," says Celestine Akpobari with a sad air: "Our life is characterized by a permanent danger with regard to health."
The comparison of wars is made.
The region where the Ogoni live has been a besieged battleground for decades: More than 60 years ago, the first European explorers entered here; the first resistance was organized in the 1980s by the writer Ken Saro-Wiwa. This was later executed. In 1993, the Shell group had to stop its production activities in this region because they had become very dangerous.
Even today, the return to the Ogoni country is forbidden to this company: While more than 2 million barrels of black gold are pumped daily thanks to more than 5000 drilling wells and 7000 kilometers of pipelines in the entire Delta region, three times as large as Switzerland, the oil fields of the Ogoni country are untapped, because the situation there is too large.
Every few hundred meters stand in the water of steel trestles like bizarre sculptures: The heads of boreholes are very affectionately referred to as "Christmas trees".
They are up to 50 years old, most are eaten by corrosion to the mark.
Akpobari believes that a drill head of this nature breaks from time to time in pieces, because a constant flow of crude oil flows into the water.
According to experts, more than two billion liters have been dumped on the ecosystem in 50 years: Each year, the amount of oil equivalent to that which flowed into the sea during the accident of the super-tanker "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago off Alaska, one of the largest environmental disasters in the history of mankind.
Who should bear responsibility for persistent environmental pollution? the answer to this question divides the actors.
For the Shell Group, sabotage and siphoning of oil pipelines are responsible for more than 90 percent of the pollution, while environmentalists consider drilling head explosions and drilled oil pipelines to be the main causes.
In 2008, the American researcher Richard Steiner criticized the Shell group for applying essentially less stringent safety standards in Nigeria than anywhere else in the world: Only the rate of pipe failures is "even higher than before".
Some forms emerge from the mangroves in a place that, seen from afar, looks like an abandoned workshop, full of camboulis and installed in the open air: They are completely naked and covered with camboulis up to the neck.
A fire sparkles under one of the many barrels that sometimes connected to the pipes, sometimes scattered for no reason on the site must be spotted: a small clandestine refinery.
The crude oil is heated in the barrel for several hours, says Michael, the team leader.
At first, gasoline enters a container by passing through pipes, then, at the end of the pipe, kerosene drops fall and diesel is finally obtained.
This is how Michael and his four collaborators produce four 300-litre diesel drums daily: "This brings us 34,000 Naira", about 22 dollars.
Delta residents are taking advantage of the chronic fuel shortage in the largest oil-producing country in black Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
Illegal refiners can sell at a lower price than the ridiculously low one of barely 40 cents per litre of Diesel: Because they acquire their raw material for free.
This is offered by the "protectors" who put the network of oil pipelines in breach throughout the country of the Ogoni. According to experts, the country loses in this way at least 16 million liters of crude oil throughout the Niger Delta.
Only a very small part of the temporarily stored raw material is illegally purified: Organized crime networks that also include high-ranking politicians and military members, load the lion’s share in tankers and sell it on the world market.
Activist Akpobari considers the debate over whether to attribute the environmental catastrophe or rather subversive activities to the population or the lax mode of production to be purely academic.
“If oil companies were not perceived as intruders and if the foundations of fishermen’s lives were not so deeply destroyed, there would be no sabotage, no theft and no illegal refineries.”
In the meantime, however, the Ogoni's relationship with Shell has deteriorated so much that it was only a matter of withdrawing from the group. "perhaps operators with other nationalities, such as the Chinese, will prove to be better."
Then Michael gets nervous.
"It's high time you got out of the way," announces the sturdy oil worker.
“Soldiers can appear at any time.”
If the illegal refiners are surprised by the special units of the armed forces, they will certainly not be arrested, but at most they will offer them bribes.
Even the soldiers, mostly from the north of the country, want to enjoy the raw material like all Nigerians.
"In every way, this damn thing has brought our country down to a very low level," Akopori said.
