Mysterious earthworks
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications regarding a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this issue, let alone submit to the agency's controls.
On the night of 5 to 6 September 2007 around midnight, at least four Israeli F-15I fighter jets attacked a mysterious cube-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is located on the bank of the Euphrates; the largest city located nearby is 30 kilometers away: it is Dair as-Sur.
His name appears in the IAEA documents, because it is about the reactor that Syria built with the help of North Korea in stone parallelepiped, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electricity.
According to a briefing by the United States intelligence services, the CIA, dating from the end of April 2008, the current reactor, known as the nearby locality, el-Kibar, would be well suited to produce plutonium, which would make it possible to manufacture atomic weapons.
On the other hand, this technique has been valid since the 1950s.
The CIA showed a presentation video featuring blurry satellite images.
Through computer-aided animation, it indicated the probable location of each reactor component before the destruction of the plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, or even the interior of it.
It seems that the reactor was about to be put into operation, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, there is barely more information available than at the time, and even, with time, the mystery deepens more and more.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that prior to the attack, the CIA was certain that Syria had built a reactor in al-Kibar, but had little evidence that the country was developing “an active nuclear weapons program.”
Some intelligence agents in Europe prefer to be more cautious about this and speak only of an “alleged reactor”, even if they consider the CIA’s presentation as “plausible”.
They lack tangible evidence, as does the IAEA.
Asked how he ensured he was dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior U.N. diplomat gave only a terse response in the summer when he said the IAEA had “sufficient documents to ask questions.”
The Syrians certainly hurriedly cleared the rubble of the “unused military building” and methodically leveled the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former chief inspector Oli Heinonen discovered traces of man-made uranium in Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA has received satellite images from commercial service providers showing the moment directly following the attack from a Member State, which appear to be more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always maintained that it has never carried out a secret atomic program and has not built a reactor.
Damascus maintains that the uranium found at the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after analyzing the particles, calling it implausible.
Since that time, Damascus has refused any discussion about it, as well as about satellite imagery.
In addition, Syria does not allow the controllers to carry out a second inspection at the site of al-Kibar and denies access to the rubble of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel remains obstinately silent.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then prime minister at the time of the attack, recently said: “We will never comment on this.”
Thus, the investigation into this case has been dragging on since June 2008 without a result and is "increasingly becoming a serious credibility problem for the Agency", as acknowledged by a high-ranking Western diplomat serving at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna, which is ultimately a serious violation of the nuclear weapons ban treaty.
The IAEA considers that to make progress, it is necessary to clarify the existence of the other three facilities that must have a "functional relationship" with the alleged reactor.
To date, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities they are, what their function is, or what they are suspected of containing.
According to information published by the newspaper "S<0xC3><0xBC>ddeutsche Zeitung", they are known within the IAEA respectively under the names of Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariyah also from the names of the neighboring cities.
The independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington, D.C., identified the locations and discovered a complex near Masyaf on satellite images that is most likely one of the suspicious objects.
It is possible that he is at or directly adjacent to a military base, which is exactly why Syria is denying IAEA inspectors access to the three sites.
In Vienna, it is alleged that the Syrians fear that the inspection group is in fact spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
To tell the truth, it was intelligence provided by American secret agents that caught the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have shuttled between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could be “used for fuel production.”
It would have “no indication of sensitive activities,” such as uranium enrichment and reprocessing; processes that are indispensable to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works thanks to unenriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible hypotheses regarding the following fundamental questions: where the uranium should have come from and where the plutonium needed to make the bomb would have been separated later.
It is unknown whether the rubble, which could hide traces of great value, was stored at all three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with earth have disappeared, no one will have information on where the rubble is stored.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located only a few kilometers from al-Kibar, on the other side of the Euphrates, examined in 1998 to see if it could be suitable for storing radioactive waste.
In analyzing recent satellite photos taken on behalf of Jane's Intelligence Review magazine, former IAEA inspector Robert Kelley linked them to the reactor in question.
Satellite photos show, however, that Syria undertook earthworks at the three suspected sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began demanding access to these locations.
It is possible that this was a coincidence, but it did not help to dismiss the suspicions.
It is said in the diplomatic circles that the IAEA has spent several months developing a plan for inspections to be carried out there. This plan was intended to allow Syria to preserve possible military secrets. Only the time invested shows how much interest the inspectors have in this case.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also flouted this proposal.
A year ago, if the Western diplomats in Vienna had not reported the destruction of the reactor, the urgency would not be reported for this case, says, for example, Glyn Davies, the US ambassador who for a few months has been talking about what is known as the special inspections, one of the most powerful means that the Atomic Agency has to implement its controls.
The Director of the IAEA, Yukiya Amano, who had to propose these inspections, has already spoken of "an option to which I am open in the future", but he still hesitates.
This means a huge risk: on the one hand, it requires a majority in the IAEA Board of Governors and many of the 35 countries represented there have no desire to see the situation escalate.
On the other hand, as this diplomat who gives to reflect: "To this it would be useful, if in the end they do not find anything"
