Since the survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it tracks changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the rather sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the South American Pacific (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy recovered after suffering a sharp drop in output last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44 per cent of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way their country's democracy worked in practice; this is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase from 25 per cent in 2001 (Chart 3).
Some 34% said they had confidence in their country's parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but up sharply from 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America undermined support for democracy.
If this has held up during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in America have experienced only a brief recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year, to 32 percent.)
But the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, translates into a widely shared sense of progress.
This is rarer in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has worsened.
It is only for the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
About 31% say they or a loved one have been the victim of a crime in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in the rise in support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is indispensable for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Graph 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their country developed, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); even though their leftist president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% from last year)
But the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A dirty vote
No one expected to have a perfect general election in Haiti on November 28.
But it was far worse than the outsiders who wanted to help the country that was devastated and in fear.
Boxes of ballots and a new ballot were presented, ballots scattered in the gutters, polling stations ransacked and intimidation
The polling stations opened late at night.
Many Haitians, including many who were displaced by the January earthquake, wandered the neighborhood to find a place to vote.
Some of them eventually gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several alleged favorites, denounced the fraud and demanded the cancellation of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, have exploded across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the senior official in Haiti of the United Nations, considers the event as "a fairly good election in many respects".
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that they “do not believe that these irregularities, however serious, necessarily invalidated the process.”
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are indebted to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, is due to announce preliminary results on December 7.
The second round is scheduled for January.
All hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial call for the vote to be declared void.
But there may be problems if Mr Célestin, who has little or no perceptible support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority to have reached the second round and reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors still living in tents, it was feared that participation would be.
In this case, many Haitians wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so due to disorganization.
Nearly 250,000 ID cards needed to vote had not yet been distributed shortly before the election.
The stakes are high.
Donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in rebuilding Haiti.
And so, of course, the Haitians do it themselves.
The tip of the feet towards the center
In the weeks after suddenly becoming a widow, Argentina’s President Cristina Fernández benefited from a wave of public sympathy that improved her approval rating by 20 points to more than 50 percent, her highest level since she was elected in 2007.
Yet turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could depend on Ms. Fernández, visibly in mourning, choosing whether or not to abandon the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Nestor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs remain confused.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, used to craft budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
Fernandez’s government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has sunk into disarray following Mr Kirchner's death from a heart attack on 27 October.
Some of the dissident members of the Peronist movement in power rallied to Ms. Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (where a congressman punched one of his peers in the face and others accused the government of corruption), Congress does not have to approve the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to argue,” the president said.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the president even more leeway to spend at will.
The economy is vastly overheating: it is likely to grow by nearly 9% this year.
The official inflation rate now stands at 11.1% but many private estimates and union wage demands, see this figure close to 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction a priority, rather than inflation control.
He refused to deal with the IMF, he harassed the private sector and purged INDEC, the statistical office, which carried out falsifications of official inflation statistics.
Can Mrs Fernández now moderate these policies?
She called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And its officials say they want to limit next year’s salary increases to 18 percent.
The economy was boosted by high world prices for Argentina's agricultural exports.
But inflation eroded the boost to growth following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Mrs Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial relations with the rest of the world.
This year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced debt restructuring for which Argentina had not settled its maturities in 2001.
Now Ms Fernández seems to be edging towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could not involve IMF surveillance, as is customary.
But last month, Economy Minister Amado Boudou announced that the Fund would provide “technical assistance” to design a new national consumer price index; which looks like a prelude to INDEC’s clean-up.
It is not clear whether Ms. Fernández wants to stay in politics beyond the end of her term, now that her husband is no longer at her side.
If it does, it needs to win the support of the middle class, among which Kirchnerism is very much advocated.
When the Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have ebbed.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether or not to quietly repudiate many of her husband’s policies.
Half a hurrah for China
Taiwanese voters have turned to a kind of closer union with the continent.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters turned out on November 27, or 70% of eligible people, to elect mayors and city councilors in five urban districts, as part of what is seen as a general assessment by President Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr. Ma himself has become a surrogate for sentiments toward the continent, having forged innovative business ties, including a partial free trade pact, in the largest reorganization of relations with China proper since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but only just.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party won three of the five town halls, it failed to win a majority of the votes.
Instead, the Democratic-Progressive Party (DPP), which leaned toward full independence from Taiwan, won nearly 50% of all votes for the 45% KMT.
If this had been a presidential election, Mr. Ma would be in trouble.
Since he was elected two years ago, his party’s share of the vote has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP attracted voters, even with the KMT in the municipal councils.
The event unveiled most of the main topics of the Taiwanese elections, including loud-campaigning trucks and mass-gathering flags with girls dancing in minimal attire.
A mandatory assassination attempt has also been carried out.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan, honorary president of the KMT, carried out an electoral tour for a KMT candidate on the eve of the election.
A man from the crowd shot the young Mr. Lien, purely through the face, wounding him and killing a passerby.
Oddly, it was not determined whether the shooter intended to harm Mr. Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
In any case, says Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PDP, the murder had consequences on the election by directing suspicion on the DPP and turning voters to the KMT.
Perhaps the biggest winner in the election was China.
It was striking how absent the question of the mainland itself was.
Instead, candidates jostled with plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan usually enjoys its de facto independence and hates China's military threat.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid parading its ties with the Beijing government.
But this time, the DPP also refrained from fanning anti-Chinese sentiment.
It is a response to a new awareness that Chinese companies are indispensable to Taiwan’s economic survival.
Ma, for his part, demanded confirmation as to whether his China policy was acceptable to the Taiwanese majority.
The Beijing government can be expected to continue to provide trade facilities, in line with its strategy to lure Taiwan back to the fold.
China wasted no time sending a negotiator to Taipei to hold a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
Admittedly, it would also like to see political integration; but let’s start from the beginning.
Better to wait for that after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has reinvented itself anyway.
Two years ago, it was going badly: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, had been sent to prison on corruption charges.
President from 2000 to 2008, he was a provocateur in favor of explicit independence.
But a new generation of moderates has emerged under Ms. Tsai’s leadership and the PDP is making every effort to attract professionals and youth.
Ms. Tsai was hailed as a DPP presidential candidate, like Su Tseng-chang, who served under Mr. Chen.
Their party is doing its best to show that it too can engage with Beijing.
Tsai announced plans for a panel of experts to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, provided their talks can take place without preconditions.
Ms. Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party presents a “trustworthy alternative” to Mr. Ma’s hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems exasperated by this change.
In a statement released from his cell, he said PDP candidates would have performed better if they had insisted that Taiwan is a separate country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatist, not to run for the presidency.
Even without Mr. Chen's intervention, the DPP will have a hard time choosing between its potential candidates.
The KMT needs to do an introspection of itself.
Mr. Ma's assessments were weak; despite dizzying economic growth, the KMT candidates did not want to campaign with him.
Its unpopularity seems to be largely due to unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman says his cabinet and local offices will be reshuffled.
The good results of the PDP suggest that Taiwan’s support for rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese see economic integration with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, "the point of no return is already past."
Grammy nominations: jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is a surprise selected in the category "best new artist"
Perform at the request of a president, and people are required to take notice of it.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer handpicked by President Obama to perform at his Nobel Peace Prize ceremony in 2009, marked one of the surprises of the Grammy Awards this year with a high-profile nomination in the category of “best new artist.”
Considering Spalding has been a well-known figure on the jazz scene since his 2008 album "Esperanza", the nomination remains somewhat mysterious but it is consistent with Grammy Award rules that an artist should not release more than three albums prior to recording; this "establishes the public identity of that artist."
His ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", certainly marked a step forward and, given his slightly engaging vocal style, his deft hand of pop and funk and his Latin influences, it is possible to draw at least a dotted line in Spalding compared to Norah Jones's meteoric success in 2003, the closest equivalent of this Grammy Award-winning production in recent years.
Elsewhere, Grammy Award voters have rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio’s “Historicity” in the “instrumental album” category, a trip on the invigorating thrill of a recording that was one of the top favorites last year.
Among these Iyer, "Moody 4B" by veteran saxophonist James Moody and "Positootly" by keyboardist John Beasley will be in competition.
Trombone Shorty, a raspy New Orleans favorite and frequent guest on HBO's "Treme," was honored in the contemporary jazz category; which also leans heavily toward a certain fusion with the albums of Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Darcy James Argue's Wild Secret Society, familiar with steampunk, won some well-deserved recognition in the big ensemble category; competing with Billy Childs' rich chamber-jazz ensemble and eternal adventurer Dave Holland whose "Pathways" album from his live octet was a fine example of this bassist's democratic hand as bandleader.
Grammy Award Nomination: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey Lead in Classic Categories
The classic nominations for the 53rd annual Grammy Awards feature a mix of landscapes from musicians and composers from around the world.
Leading the nominations are Michael Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina," for piano and orchestra, with five "yeses"; and Steve Mackey's "Dreamhouse," an electric orchestral work, with three "yeses."
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California is Estonian composer Arvo P<0xC3><0xA4>rt for his Symphony No. 4, “Los Angeles,” a work that was commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and opened the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
The Madolin Concerto by Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also in the running for an award.
The classical nominations are divided into 13 categories covering orchestral, opera, choral and solo recordings.
A category for Classic Producer of the Year features five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
Nominations for the classic album include Bruckner's Symphonies No. 3 and 4 of the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey's "Dreamhouse" of the Boston Modern Orchestra Various Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrifium" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; and "Sacrifium" of the Art of the Boston Modern Orchestra.
In the category of opera, the nominees are "Lulu" by Berg of the Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Adolf Hasse of the Ars Lyrica Houston; "L'Amour de Loin" by Kaija Saariaho of the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; "The Enchanted Wanderer" by Rodion Shchedrin's BBC Orchestra and "The Enchanted Wanderer" of the Berlin Symphony.
Composers who are in place for the Grammy Awards for contemporary composition include P<0xC3><0xA4>rt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appasionatamente Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Wanderer Enchanted".
P<0xC3><0xA4>rt's Symphony No. 4 had its premiere at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a performance recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The approximately 30-minute work is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to former oil magnate Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" was nominated for his instrumental solo performance with an orchestra.
The Los Angeles-based composer said he is soon writing the 15-minute work especially for mandolin performer Avi Avital, who played the concerto with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
“I wrote it using Middle Eastern sounds and a lot of North African scales and rhythms,” Dorman said in a phone interview.
Conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, received a nomination in the orchestral performance category for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra in a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Instrumental soloists nominated include pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
This year, there are only female vocalist-soloist nominees; here they are: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucie Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the category of classical mixes, soprano Jessye Norman received a nomination for her recording "Roots: My Life, My Song"
The Temecula Mosque project wins the approval of the planning commission.
A mosque project in Temecula received unanimous support from the local planning commission after more than five hours of public, often impassioned testimony.
Critics attacked the project, claiming that it promoted both terrorism and traffic jams.
But the commissioners ruled Wednesday night that the new religious center respected local laws and would be aesthetically impressive.
"A lot of good people have come to support it: Christians, Jews, Baha'is, you mention it," said Hadi Nael, president of the Temecula Valley Islamic Center, speaking Thursday morning.
"I'm proud of that, as an American citizen."
"It shows that justice prevails."
“The opposition is really minimal,” he added.
“They just have very strong voices.”
"We have good people in this valley."
The session began at 6 p.m. and lasted until almost midnight with, most of the time, people speaking for or against the center, with speaking time roughly evenly distributed, according to the Press-Enterprise.
The debate continued on the newspaper’s website.
“There is no more America,” one speaker wrote.
"This is another planet of monkeys with Miss Liberty dead in the sand."
“America has fallen.”
Planned Islamic centers have also sparked protests in other parts of the country, including at Ground Zero, the site of the September 11, 2001 attacks in New York City.
Imam Mahmoud Harmoush denounced violence in the Temecula Valley.
Her congregation of about 135 families has co-existed without incident in Riverside County for years but she wanted a larger and better space than the warehouse she rented on a property shared with a manufacturer of water filtration systems.
The new 24,943-square-foot mosque with Mediterranean-style architecture would consist of two minarets and rise to 43 feet in height.
It would occupy a 4.32-hectare site on Route Nicolas about two miles east of Chaparral High School.
Opponents can still appeal against this project to the city council.
An arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, widens the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that were considered essential.
"This organization has a double capacity."
"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That's why it's very special, even though it's far from a truly 'foreign' life form," said Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But the researchers found that the bacterium, discovered in Mono Lake, California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“One wonders what is still possible,” said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, Anbar says.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not divulge the details of the find, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could divulge the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms might be able to use other elements to drive biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements, which we deem absolutely necessary for life, might not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Institute for Planetary and Space Science Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It was not a fortuitous discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to the two substances might be able to substitute for each other.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus.”
"As a result, organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
“But arsenic is different enough that it doesn’t work exactly like phosphorus; it gets inside and sort of erases the work of our biochemical machine,” Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows best with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a life form using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing ever showed that it could work.
Arsenic was more common early in Earth’s existence, she says, so researchers have speculated that early life could have used it.
This suggests that there might be other ways to form life, not just the way life on Earth was formed in the beginning,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
Last two stolen show dogs found in Compton
The other two show dogs on four stolen from outside a Bellflower motel were found, Los Angeles County sheriffs announced Thursday.
The four show dogs — two akitas and two Welsh Pembroke corgis — went missing Tuesday when someone stole the Chevrolet Express pickup truck in which they had spent the night outside a Bellflower Motel 6, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were recovered Wednesday afternoon and the other two were found late Wednesday evening, Los Angeles County Sheriff’s Department spokesman Steve Whitmore told reporters.
“The good news is that the dogs are doing well,” Whitmore says.
“They are in good shape.”
"They have been returned to their rightful owners."
Whitmore declined to say precisely where the dogs had been found, in what neighborhood, and what the circumstances of their discovery were.
"An investigation is underway."
“We don’t want to say it,” Whitmore said.
"We follow orders."
Owners Kristina Rickard and David Peek could not be reached for comment Thursday.
They were reunited Wednesday afternoon with their two Akitas at a county animal shelter in Downey.
Sheriff's deputies found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
The Akitas — Trace, a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old female — were safe, authorities said.
But Bunny and Peter, the corgis that Rickard and Peek had planned to show at regional competitions this week, on behalf of the owners of the Japanese dogs, were missing until their discovery Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, are in town this weekend as part of the AKC/Eukanuba Long Beach National Championship, where they planned to host Trace.
The other dogs were expected to compete in other events scheduled in the days leading up to the “AKC/Eukanuba” exhibition, Peek told The Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is one of the stops on the couple’s nearly month-long dog show tour.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van outside, right next to their bedroom window.
They took three other dogs – a Boxer puppy, a Parson Russell terrier and a Breton spaniel – who stayed with them in the motel room.
But they left the Akitas and the corgis, with thicker fur, in the van where it would be cooler.
They opened the windows a bit, so the dogs could get some fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the van stolen at 6 a.m.
Peek said they would offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the corgis, fitted with a microchip implanted to identify them.
It is not clear if a prize was awarded on Thursday.
The lion is ready to blush again, the restructuring of MGM is waiting for the final green light from the court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start over.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York on Thursday officially praised the creditors’ “pre-packaged” plan that would clear about $5 billion of debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and distributing movies and TV shows.
With Thursday’s decision that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, no legal hurdles remain for MGM to recover under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the CEOs of what will be a lean studio.
Staff will be reduced to about 320 out of 400 initially.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase enters into a $500 million credit facility to fund MGM’s new operations and productions.
It is currently being licensed by the investment bank, which is struggling with $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The studio’s restructuring process began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to place its finances as it could not afford to pay the $300 million per year interest.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and recovery expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper’s attempts to resolve MGM’s financial difficulties and satisfy the studio’s more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed at the end of 2009 to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the additional $2 billion sought by creditors.
In the spring of this year, everything had to be done again as the MGM team had begun work on a restructuring plan that, after months of disagreements and internal debates, was finally approved by creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially exited bankruptcy in the following weeks, the Moelis and Cooper companies received multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already raised $1.2 million, will receive a $9.5 million payment.
Cooper’s companies, which have raised $375,000 per month for their corporate management services, will receive a “success premium” of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plans to revive MGM’s production, which has only released one film this year, and put together an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released starting in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on “The Hobbit” with Warner Bros.
The studio must make a separate loan between $265 million and $275 million to finance its share in these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who holds about 18 percent of MGM’s debt, has attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the main shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not resulted in an agreement.
Tech toys to keep your gift budget in balance
Although the top contender for this year’s most wonderful toy is the iPad, followed, perhaps, by Microsoft’s video game system, Kinect, both can make a significant dent in your gift budget.
Consider that, for the price of an iPad, you can buy five $99 BMX bikes, and that a Kinect game costs the same price as 10 classic jump ropes of beads, or about 48 boxes of Play-Doh.
But there are ways to keep your gift budget in balance.
Recently, I visited three national toy sellers - Wal-Mart, Toys "R" Us and BJ's Wholesale Club - to see the electronic toys I could buy for less than $80.
Clearly Moore’s Law has evolved, this year’s tech toy is likely to have more force; while costing the same price if not a little less, compared to last year.
Also, while there are generally fewer new toys associated with websites, two of the more well-known of this type, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more offers.
And button battery toys are on the rise, as well as rechargeable battery toys.
Here are some recommendations.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us, unless otherwise noted.)
The Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13 for 3 years and older) are stuffed toys the size of a guinea pig that sing a note when you squeeze them on the belly.
One pressure is equal to one note, and a second allows you to compose a song.
If you buy several, they will sing in harmony.
Warning: once you start to press, you can’t stop.
To combine singing with dancing, Dance Mickey Star (Fisher-Price, $60 for 2 years and over) is the best choice.
Taking inspiration from last year’s Elmo Live technology, the 14-inch animatronic doll plays turn-based games like Simon Says and can do the moon dance thanks to its innovative wheel-locking articulating feet.
Children who have tried the toy use Mickey as a dance instructor while their parents complain of a lack of volume control.
If you are a child of the 80s, you will remember Alphie, one of the first computerized educational toys.
He’s back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40 for 3+ years), with a backpack filled with quiz game cards designed to turn a ride in car into a session with self-correction and a valve binder.
If you’re suspicious when your child is holding your smartphone, here are three stand-alone alternatives.
The VTech Mobigo ($60, for 3 to 8 year olds) is the cheapest and easiest to use, with a qwerty keyboard, although the games do not educate as effectively as the Leapster Explorer ($70, for 3 to 12 year olds), it is the first major overhaul of the Leapster range, with a newer and brighter display.
No version is compatible with older cartridges.
The Fisher-Price iXL ($90, for ages 3-7) uses an iTunes-like system to offer games and e-books, and comes with an SD card input that lets you view family photos.
Finally, Scrabble Flash ($30, Hasbro, for ages 8 and up) is a set of five blocks barely bigger than a matchbox, each with its own LED screen.
The goal is to form words by placing the blocks online before time runs out, this is ideal for an impromptu spelling contest.
More and more, toys have some kind of online connection.
