Bringing a Softer Side to Law Enforcement in China
Tang Shenbin paced a city square like an urban sergeant in training by inspecting his nerve charges severely, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan—imposing law enforcement officials in China, feared and despised for their arbitrary repression and penchant for violence—to convey a certain impression to a set of spectators.
"Stand up!"
"Be perceptive!"
Show them, he says, "what pretty girls look like!"
Four girls who had barely passed their teenage years in white gloves, dressed in identical olive-colored jackets and trousers, froze at the guard.
Four pairs of black heeled shoes, aligned to the rule.
Four neat hats perched perfectly on top of hair tied by a blue and white striped knot.
"Personally, I think they look average," Tang said, disdainfully.
"The models are pretty."
More than one government has tried to refresh the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city required all new recruits to have a higher education degree.
Guangdong Province has swapped the gray-green uniforms for a supposedly more engaging blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the lower-eyes with the strong way:: In 2009, a report reported that 50 officers had surrounded an uncontrollable snack cart by casting black glances, firmly for half an hour, until the peddler packed up his belongings and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, chose to do a big image operation.
Since 2003, the district has completed its urban street policing of 13 women, specially chosen for their appearance, body shape and young age.
The idea is to give the skinned police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson might have a hard time drawing attention to China’s underground urban brigade.
And for good reason, critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce municipal ordinances by imposing fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media portrays the news as a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei province beat an observer to death after he used his mobile phone to film them dispersing a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors, stolen and posted online, described how to effectively defeat offenders without emitting blood.
This year in Shanghai, a watermelon peddler was abandoned with a brain injury after a fight with five officers.
A video game steeped in violence, available via online download, shows Chinese inspectors trained to assault street vendors.
“Chengguan has marked the government,” China Daily, a national publication, lamented last year after yet another controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for a "genuine complete clean-up."
Skeptics say the approach is a long way off.
After the district made an announcement in October to find eight new female recruits, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News questioned whether women had real tasks or were just tourist entertainment.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district’s announcement required female candidates, ages 18 to 22, to have a beautiful figure and “five facial features in the right order.”
They must be above average size, either 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1<0xE2><0x81><0x84>2 inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is mandatory.
Officers said the work was too physically burdensome for women over the age of 25.
