"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they are suitable; it is the size, weight, facial features, etc."
Then come the temperament and the “inner qualities.”
Chengguan women are like flower vases, he said, adding: “In addition to being vases, they will have other responsibilities.
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the city's district management office, does not agree with this description.
But he noted that height requirements were the standard in many Chinese job postings for both sexes.
This is the case of the requirement relating to the order of the facial features.
That it means beautiful is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Of course, disabled or disfigured people should not apply.
“We can’t let a limping person or a hunchback come and serve here,” Zheng said.
“It wouldn’t give a good image.”
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old and has cheekbones with a finely curved mouth.
She doesn’t consider highlighting her appearance as sexist, she said.
“Do you think I look sexy in that uniform?” she asked disillusionedly.
Xu Yang, his dimpled 21-year-old colleague, says: “Our job is to present the image of the city.”
They don’t object to their mandate being limited, they said, because they have bigger career ambitions than just chasing salespeople down the alleys where they’re supposed to limit their activities.
