Like female officers, coordinators - men aged 40 or over - play a purely supportive role.
Unlike them, they are not formed in order to maintain a waxed image.
“Sometimes we fight verbally.”
“Sometimes we fight physically,” Mr. Li said in a neutral tone.
“Most of the time, it’s the audience that starts.”
Prosecutors Won't Charge Senator Ensign
Attorneys for the Department of Justice have dropped criminal charges against Senator John Ensign stemming from a case involving a former campaign aide and his efforts to secure a lobbying job for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers said Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Mr Ensign's office said he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign’s lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had “reported that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to pursue any charges against him in this matter.”
The Department of Justice declined to comment.
The announcement came as a kind of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator’s affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once served as treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an associate of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole for one year.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual deal between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seems at odds with the so-called revolving door lobbying ban.
Based on the evidence that has been made public, “there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violation of the revolving door law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients from an investigation by the government.
Although the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in Ensign, Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-profile setbacks suffered by its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop prosecutions against former Senator Ted Stevens.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the executive director of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, an advocacy group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign’s senior lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call on Monday from a Justice Department prosecutor and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not seeking charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign’s legal team had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
“I’m not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Mr. Ensign’s parents’ $96,000 payment to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign’s chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was “hammering” the Department of the Interior over a disputed issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Mr. Hampton in lobbying.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth-ranking Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intends to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
