Can civility bridge the divides?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a modicum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of genuine bipartisan forward cooperation or an illusory moment before the quick return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that need to be addressed during the “lame duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was just as civilized, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of testing and testing each other for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to gauge the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent comments from participants unveiled a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxation, spending, health care or entitlements, the two sides remain miles apart.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed on the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now with the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions, and then they fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on extending unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is hovering over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "lame duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the blade duck session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
“I consider most of what’s going on between now and 2012 as pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea party that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, raising the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, in their own words, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected representatives of the group, which suggests that there is little motivation or willingness to compromise on fiscal issues, at least today.
Galston envisions two phases in the fighting between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care; then it will be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will watch the public reaction carefully.
The one who will be judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
However, that would be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consequential election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
US documents released describe Moscow as a haven for corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a “Kleptocracy” and passes some of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia said in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are carrying out huge rackets that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Each layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical of power” – takes its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by WikiLeaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been redacted.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there have been few signs of clean-up since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Baturina, who owns a leading construction company, have always denied corruption charges over the years; and he has won several defamation lawsuits over these charges.
In September, he said the following to a Russian TV channel, when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: “It’s crazy, it’s toss, it’s whatever.”
The Russians believe, by an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to the polls.
But it is unusual to find the information stated in an embassy report; and it is unheard of to conceive that it would be to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link established between the Moscow city government and crime has led some people to call it “dysfunctional” and claim that the government functions more like a kleptocracy than a government.
Criminal elements enjoy a “krysha” (a term used in the criminal/mafia world that literally means “roof” or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor’s office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"The analysts identify a three-tiered structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
“The FSB, MVD and militias are at the second level.”
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a gap in certain areas where the city does not provide certain services.”
The report says the FSB is siphoning off money from the biggest companies and police are targeting the small ones.
A source, he said, “explained that Moscow business owners understood that it was better to get protection from the MVD and the FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because, not only do they have more weapons, more means and more power than criminal groups but they are also protected by law.”
“That’s why the demand for protection from criminal gangs is no longer as high.”
The memo notes that although the collection of money is extensive, the protection itself may be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their business closed under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has mentioned the fight against corruption several times but has admitted little progress.
The embassy's memo relays reports of men bringing suitcases, probably filled with money, to the Kremlin.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev depends on bureaucrats," Georgy Satarov, director of Moscow's Indem think tank, said in a recent interview.
“But he’s part of that bureaucracy.”
“He is not part of a political class because there is no political class in Russia.”
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, corruption is inevitable.
