An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The stakes are clear.
And it would be bad not to hear it.
It is not just a question of bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked to do is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will allow greater tranquility to come to us.
And that we know how to seize the opportunity we were given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after the meeting of the past Saturday with the big companies and the announcement of new measures yesterday) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticisms, the way has been opened to the thesis that we must put order at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don’t seem to move it.
