Sport and the Fraud of the Law
The tricks similar to those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
The expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has cast a lot of ink on the unsportsmanlike character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is known, a few minutes before finishing the match (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of its group, both players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next game of the play-off match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and various economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that emerged in the case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which on past occasions has condemned to a fine to its players for similar acts) and to the provocative dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to his story.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour is not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether with these actions a fraud of law is committed; because, indeed, they are actions respectful with the sports regulation, but seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sportsmanship.
One of the assets that includes sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put at risk, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with correct play is to prevent the team of offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out secretly to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They were waiting and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders obtain from the intentional misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action supposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club could not rely on these players.
Obviously the advantage lies in the fact that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty game and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, moving up the ladder, it's not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sportsmanship, which is still part of making strategic decisions that promote maximum profit from what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), but otherwise they chose rather the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the line between engineering and the fraud of the law is blurred, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of engineering.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way of transmitting the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
