The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the wait time cost will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (VSA) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (this includes visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not be required to appear for an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra $26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application process, visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bulletins/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
