A global plan to renovate lighting
The UN proposed yesterday in Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) that corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction that must be achieved to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan follows on from the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, the bulk of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the global car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance sheet to be able to stabilize the rise of the climate to 2 degrees centigrade by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates as heat and the rest, 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice as much.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about CFLs as they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous wastes, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up guidelines.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make through this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
