The American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal some of the undersides of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysee explained its strategy to the Americans, going so far as to give them advice for dealing with their own “hostage” crises in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials have sought to convince Washington that the release of the young Frenchwoman did not have the counterpart of the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and wanted by the American justice for trafficking materials for the benefit of the Iranian nuclear program.
Finally, they cast a stark light on how the French presidency sought to manipulate the media into accrediting the idea that Syrian President Bashar al-Assad had played a central role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
In reality, it was nothing.
A diplomatic telegram written on 12 August 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French comments on how to handle hostage cases".
The Elysee's advisor for strategic affairs, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d'Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, speak with the American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain to him the French method.
They advise Americans to do the same to repatriate their own nationals forcibly detained in Iran.
“Make a noise,” they say, “hammer incessantly” in the media the words “fundamental human rights,” “innocent,” “immediate liberation.”
This is necessary in order to embarrass the Iranian regime, which is sensitive to its image.
"Do it all the more as the Iranians are asking you not to do it."
Because, after attempts to discuss through discreet channels, "silence will not solve anything", the Iranians are "masters in delaying maneuvers".
Richier added that the arrest of foreigners is “a familiar Iranian tactic: taking hostages for political blackmail.”
He announces that the release from prison of Clotilde Reiss (which will take place on August 16, the day she takes refuge at the French Embassy) "will require the payment to the Iranians of a large sum of money" (230,000 euros in bail).
And he says the Elysée anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that "will worsen".
The Iranians could "in the near future arrest another of the some 1,800 French citizens living in Iran," he said.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss has been out of prison for 12 days, but remains stranded in Iran.
Iranian Majid Kakavand, whose extradition the United States is demanding for illegal trafficking of sensitive electronic equipment to Iran, is released in Paris on the decision of a judge.
The U.S. Embassy, like many observers, wonders about this disturbing coincidence.
For Washington, which is tracking Iran’s clandestine networks for acquiring equipment for the nuclear program, the expansion of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Did France agree to a bargain?
The liberation of the Iranian against that of the French?
In a new interview with Kathleen Allegrone, on September 4, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Richier assures that this is not the case.
The Elysee, he said, not only “was completely taken by surprise by the judge’s decision,” but sought to oppose it.
"There were lively exchanges between the French presidency and the guardian of the seals" (at the time, Mich<0xC3><0xA8>le Alliot-Marie), but "the French government cannot reverse the decision", he observes.
Mr Richier also wants to show that Majid Kakavand remains under the "close" surveillance of the French intelligence services.
The adviser of the Elysee dials a phone number, hangs up, and then informs the American diplomat that the Iranian "is currently located in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian embassy."
During the detention of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elysée spares no effort, through communiqués and "leaks" organized in the media, to make believe that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad plays an "important" and "influential" role as "mediator".
The Americans observe this activity not without irony, and note that the manipulation bears fruit since several press articles echo the official French version.
A telegram dated August 25, 2009 evokes "the media 'blitz' of French officials".
On what is so much "gratitude" expressed to Mr. Assad, asks the embassy in Paris.
“Despite their laudatory statements, French officials privately acknowledge that they have only a vague notion of what the Syrians actually did.”
The document then looks at the reasons that led the Elysée to pour into this fiction.
The intense communication effort "is aimed at validating Sarkozy's policy of openness to Syria," he said.
A policy launched in 2008, which "had then been perceived, by many critical voices in France and abroad, as premature and undeserved".
By “exaggerating the Syrian role”, Paris seeks to “demonstrate to Syria what praise it can attract by playing a constructive role in the region”.
The goal is also to “sow seeds of discord between Syria and Iran.”
The U.S. Embassy knows this from a good source.
On August 11, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Richier told him: "Of course, we don't know if the Syrians did anything."
“But we thanked them anyway.”
“This should at least cause confusion among Iranians.”
Clotilde Reiss returned to France on 16 May 2010.
Nicolas Sarkozy receives her at the Elysee Palace.
In a statement, he thanked the presidents of Brazil, Senegal and Syria for their "active role in favor of the liberation of our compatriot".
