Vengeful Hackers and Spies in Diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals itself as an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's do it in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file made up of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those owned by Berlusconi), and the sinisterly caricatured profile of Gaddafi had long been for the artists of cabaret sketch material.
The rule that secret files should be composed only of news already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do new research (nor does he know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and who reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
Same goes for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what do I know, editor at Liberation), who holds as true only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as Newsweek had published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representative exercises, have turned into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to cast a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secretive secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims as much in crisis as the "burreaux".
But let’s get to the deeper nature of what happened.
Back in Orwell’s day, you could think of all power as a Big Brother controlling every move of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker — elected as the citizen’s avenger — can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is true, too, that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but has done too much harm to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information online - that would be to publish it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
There is nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew in and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and therefore romantic, but I am forced to imagine government agents who move discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, i.e. backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-established a telegraph over (telephone) wires.
The (analog) videocassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to skip from chapter to chapter, that is to say by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, one goes from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the journeys it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is not extraordinary, therefore, that politics and communication techniques should revert to horse-drawn carriages.
One last observation.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
Now, it is the embassies that are asking the press for confidential information.
