While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as the reference year: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 are "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to “new and additional” financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ loaned is equivalent to 1€ given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is false to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given ... At most, should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan for the lending country (i.e. the equivalent rate of interest).
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to make such extensive use of the loan.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its commitment, France spends only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
That's a nice sleight of hand!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to make believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early funding is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to the whole climate discussion.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this is not the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the talks.
Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (formerly Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value with regard to the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", bought between July and September the food usually consumed in four meals and a snack in a day by a child of about ten years, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including the official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as treats, were examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is overwhelming: 81 chemical substances of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear from our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven to be certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemicals including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for Kenyan green beans, included in the luncheon, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, minced steak, canned tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were loaded with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to warm the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The ultimate risk to the consumer of this “contaminant cocktail” “is probably underestimated,” according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "faced with the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
